'''Giles Deacon''' (born 1969) is a British [[fashion designer]], best known for his playful designs and his collaboration with High Street retailer [[New Look (clothing retailer)|New Look]]. Deacon was employed by the fashion houses [[Bottega Veneta]] and [[Gucci]], before founding his own label, GILES, in 2003. He launched his first collection for GILES at the 2004 [[London Fashion Week]] and was named "Best New Designer" at the [[British Fashion Awards]]. Deacon's designs have been met with critical acclaim and have sparked a renewed interest in London fashion. Having become one of the fashion industry's most f<U+00EA>ted figures, Deacon was named [[British Fashion Awards|British Fashion Designer of the Year]] in 2006 and was awarded the French ANDAM Fashion Award's Grand Prix in 2009.

==Early Life==
Deacon was born in [[Darlington]], [[County Durham]], but grew up near [[Ullswater]] in the [[Lake District]].<ref name="GilesKing">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/giles-deacon-king-of-london-435540.html|title=Giles Deacon: King of London|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|date=10 February 2007|accessdate=21 January 2010<!-- |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5pBlagc10|archivedate=22 April 2010 -->}}</ref><ref name="EditorsLoveGiles">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2008/sep/07/fashion|title=Why the fashion editors love Giles|last=Barber|first=Lynn|date=7 September 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=13 April 2010<!-- |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5pBlsnfHW|archivedate=22 April 2010 -->}}</ref> Deacon is the youngest child of David, an agricultural salesman and Judith, a housewife. He has one older sister.<ref name="LdnEveningStandard">{{cite news|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/fashion/article-23714789-giles-deacon-cutting-a-splash.do|title=Giles Deacon: Cutting A Splash|last=Slater|first=Lydia|date=3 July 2009|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|accessdate=21 April 2010<!-- |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5pBmFuYpm|archivedate=22 April 2010 -->}}</ref><ref name="EditorsLoveGiles"/> He attended [[Barnard Castle School]] in County Durham and later Harrogate College of Arts, where he completed an art foundation course.<ref name="EditorsLoveGiles"/><ref name="GilesUnlikelyLad">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/6662440/Giles-Deacon-The-unlikely-lad-of-fashion.html|title=Giles Deacon: The unlikely lad of fashion|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|first=Lucy|last=Cavendish|date=1 December 2009|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> After completing his foundation course he went on to study at [[Central Saint Martins College of Art and Design|Central St Martins]] and was in the same class as fashion designers [[Alexander McQueen]] and [[Luella Bartley]].<ref name="GilesTelegraph">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/paris-fashion-week/6246174/Paris-Fashion-Week-celebrates-20-years-of-ANDAM.html|title=British designer Giles Deacon wins French fashion's 2009 'grand prix'|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|first=Hilary|last=Alexander|date=30 September 2009|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="Stylemag">{{cite web|url=http://www.stylemag-online.net/2008/12/10/giles-deacon-interview/|title=Giles Deacon Interview|last=Rothe|first=Marcus|date=10 December 2008|publisher=Style Magazine|accessdate=21 March 2010}}</ref> He graduated in 1992 and began collaborating on the label 'Doran Deacon' with his friend, Fi Doran as well as contributing illustrations to [[Dazed & Confused (magazine)|Dazed & Confused]].<ref name="GilesKing"/>

==Career==
Deacon choose to travel and gain experiences at fashion houses, before starting his own label.<ref name="Stylemag"/> During his time in [[Paris]], Deacon was hired to work with fashion designer [[Jean-Charles de Castelbajac]], where he learnt how to use a brand name commercially.<ref name="Stylemag"/><ref name=GilesBiography>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonfashionweek.co.uk/designers/documents/doc_1347.doc|title=Giles Biography|publisher=[[London Fashion Week]]|accessdate=15 February 2010|format=Doc}}</ref> Deacon worked with Castelbajac for two years, before returning to London to work for High Street fashion houses. During this time, Deacon met the owner of Italian luxury goods house, [[Bottega Veneta]], and was hired to work for the company, becoming the head designer and debuting a much acclaimed collection in 2000.<ref name="Stylemag"/><ref name="GilesAnAudience">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/fashion/features/giles-deacon-an-audience-with-the-king-of-british-fashion-1915500.html|title=Giles Deacon: An audience with the king of British fashion|date=6 March 2010|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=11 March 2010}}</ref> Deacon was dismissed in 2001 when the [[Gucci]] group brought the company and terminated his contract, so they could hire German designer, [[Tomas Maier]].<ref name="LdnEveningStandard"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/fashion/article1341450.ece|title=Britain<U+2019>s Deacon of light|date=7 February 2007|work=[[The Times]]|publisher=[[News International|Times Newspapers Ltd]]|accessdate=21 April 2010}}</ref> However, he was immediately hired by [[Tom Ford]] to assist with Gucci womenswear.<ref name="GilesAnAudience"/><ref name="GilesRecord">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-interviews/2008/05/17/designer-giles-deacon-tells-how-he-rose-to-the-top-in-the-fashion-world-86908-20420418/|title=Designer Giles Deacon Tells How He Rose To The Top|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|first=Lindsay|last=Clydesdale|date=17 May 2008|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> Deacon was forced to leave Gucci after one season when he became ill from an infected saliva gland.<ref name="GilesUnlikelyLad"/>  

Once he had recovered, Deacon decided to take out a loan to start his own label and he launched GILES in 2003.<ref name="GilesTelegraph"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/lifestyle/article.html?Giles_collection_%91inspired_by_Pac-Man%92.&in_article_id=312744&in_page_id=194|title=Giles collection <U+2018>inspired by Pac-Man<U+2019>|work=[[Metro (Associated Metro Limited)|Metro]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|date=17 September 2008|accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> He launched his first collection at London Fashion Week in February 2004, styled by his friend Katie Grand, the show saw models [[Karen Elson]], [[Lily Cole]], [[Eva Herzigova]] and [[Linda Evangelista]] walking the catwalk.<ref name="GilesAnAudience"/> The collection received international acclaim and began a renewed interest in London fashion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fashionunited.co.uk/News/Columns/Giles_Deacon%92s_fashion_in_motion_200906227342/|title=Giles Deacon<U+2019>s Fashion In Motion|publisher=Fashion United|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> Deacon regularly shows at London Fashion Week and the GILES collection is brought by over thirty retail stores including [[Barneys New York|Barneys]], [[Harvey Nichols]] and [[Selfridges]].<ref name="GilesAnAudience"/><ref name=GilesBiography/><ref name="EditorsLoveGiles"/> Deacon counts [[Thandie Newton]], [[Princess Beatrice of York|Princess Beatrice]] and [[Scarlett Johansson]] among his clients.<ref name="NYMag">{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/fashion/fashionshows/designers/bios/gilesdeacon/|title=Giles Deacon - Designer Fashion Label|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|publisher=New York Media Holdings|accessdate=21 March 2010}}</ref> Since Deacon launched his label, he has seen the turnover double every year and sales increase during the [[Late 2000s recession in Europe#United Kingdom|recession]].<ref name="LdnEveningStandard"/>  

===Style===
{{Quote_box |width=21% |align=right|quote= "Hopefully, if you saw someone wearing one of our frocks you'd think she looks quite interesting to have a chat with and say hello to. They're a bit 'We're on, we're out, we mean business."<ref name="NYMag"/>|source=<U+2014> Deacon on his designs.}} 
Deacon has been known to challenge the traditional ideas of womenswear and often uses wild prints and [[Popular culture|pop culture]] references in his designs.<ref name="NYMag"/><ref name="Reuters">{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSLG24037120080917|title=Pac-Man the muse for London designer Giles Deacon|last=Motevalli|first=Golnar|date=16 September 2008|work=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|accessdate=21 March 2010}}</ref> He has described his designs for GILES as humorous, dark and sexy and has stated that he wants diversity in among them.<ref name="Stylemag"/> He said, "My dresses should be worn by young, cool girls just as much as by 55 to 60 year old women".<ref name="Stylemag"/> At the 2008 London Fashion Week, Deacon presented a collection with a futuristic theme based on the 1980s arcade game [[Pac-Man]]. The character was embellished on many of the dresses and the models wore oversized helmets in the shape of Pac-Man.<ref name="Reuters"/> Deacon's [[New Look (clothing retailer)|New Look]] menswear collections have been described by ''[[GQ]]'' magazine as "straddling the line between quirky and wearable".<ref name="GQ">{{cite web|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/men-of-the-year/moty-2009/winners/gq-moty-giles-deacon,-gq-designer-of-the-year-|title=Giles Deacon: GQ Designer Of The Year|work=[[GQ]]|publisher=Cond<U+00E9>NetUK Limited|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref>

On Deacon's style, fashion website [[Style.com]] has said, "His work is randomness incarnate. It can't keep to any one message, or develop an intellectual thesis. If you're looking for a point, he'll never get to it".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.style.com/fashionshows/review/S2008RTW-GDEACON/|title=Giles Spring 2008 Ready-To-Wear|last=Mower|first=Sarah|date=19 September 2007|work=[[Style.com]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|accessdate=21 March 2010}}</ref>

===Collaborations===
Deacon has worked on many collaborations with companies including [[British Sky Broadcasting|Sky]], [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]] and Evoke, with whom he created his first jewellery collection.<ref name="GilesAnAudience"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfashionlife.com/archives/2008/08/08/giles-for-evoke-giles-deacon-to-launch-his-first-ever-jewellery-collection/|title=Giles for Evoke: Giles Deacon to Launch his First Ever Jewellery Collection|last=Obi|first=Michele|date=8 August 2008|work=My Fashion Life|publisher=My Life Media Ltd|accessdate=21 March 2010}}</ref> Deacon has called collaborations "practical", because they "bring the money you need for your own company".<ref name="Stylemag"/>

In a two season collaboration with British fashion company [[Mulberry (company)|Mulberry]], Deacon introduced a line of accessories called "Mulberry for Giles", which was both a commercial and critical success.<ref name=GilesBiography/> Deacon was then appointed to design for the classic British tailoring label, Daks.<ref name="GilesKing"/> He showed his first and second collections for the brand in 2007 and his third in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.style.com/fashionshows/review/F2007RTW-DAKS|title=Daks by Giles Deacon|work=[[Style.com]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|first=Sarah|last=Mower|date=22 February 2007|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.style.com/fashionshows/review/S2008RTW-DAKS|title=Daks by Giles Deacon|work=[[Style.com]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|first=Sarah|last=Mower|date=28 September 2007|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.style.com/fashionshows/review/F2008RTW-DAKS|title=Daks by Giles Deacon|work=[[Style.com]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|first=Nicole|last=Phelps|date=20 February 2008|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref>

In 2009, Deacon designed and created a strapless dress with polka dots for the Cadbury's Caramel Bunny, to celebrate the launch of [[Cadbury Dairy Milk Caramel|Caramel Nibbles]].<ref name="GilesCadbury">{{cite web|url=http://www.handbag.com/fashion/Giles-Deacon-designs-Cadbury's-Caramel-Nibbles-Bunny-dress/v1|title=Giles has designs on Cadbury|publisher=Handbag|first=Leisa|last=Barnett|date=16 October 2009|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> A limited edition scarf was also created and 1400 were given away via the world's first online Pop Up Boutiques.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://style.uk.msn.com/advertorials/cadburys-nibbles/features.aspx|title=Style Icon Meets Design Genius For New Nibbles Collection|work=[[MSN]]|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> The scarf then went on sale at selected [[John Lewis (department store)|John Lewis]] stores and online.<ref name="GilesCadbury"/> In the same year, Deacon teamed up with Norwegian water company [[List_of_soft_drinks_by_country#Norway|Isklar]] and created a limited edition [[Tote bag]] with 50 per cent of the proceeds from each bag sold going to [[Oxfam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gilesdeaconisklar.com/index.html|title=Limited Editon Isklar Tote Designed By Giles Deacon|publisher=Isklar|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref>

Deacon's best known collaboration has been with the [[High Street]] fashion chain [[New Look (clothing retailer)|New Look]]. The collection called Gold by Giles began in March 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fashionunited.co.uk/Content_by_Mail/Received_content/Giles_Deacon_designs_for_New_Look_200609071397/|title=Giles Deacon designs for New Look|publisher=Fashion United|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> On choosing to collaborate with the clothing retailer, Deacon said: "I chose New Look as the high street store to work with, as we both have a sense of fun and believe in fashion for everyone."<ref name="GilesGold">{{cite web|url=http://www.fashionunited.co.uk/News/Columns/Gold_by_Giles_Deacon_200801292515/|title=Gold by Giles Deacon|publisher=Fashion United|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> 
Actress [[Drew Barrymore]] starred in the first ad campaigns for the collection, following a chance meeting between her and the designer in a lift.<ref name="GilesVogue">{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/biographies/080422-giles-deacon-biography.aspx|title=Giles Deacon Biography|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|first=Jo|last=Craven|date=22 April 2008|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a43868/drew-barrymore-to-model-for-new-look.html|title=Drew Barrymore to model for New Look|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=Digital Spy Limited|first=Nick|last=Levine|date=13 March 2007|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> British model, [[Agyness Deyn]] took over and modelled the key pieces for Deacon's 4th collection.<ref name="GilesGold"/> Deacon's first menswear collection debuted in 2008 and his first beachwear collection launched in early June 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fashionunited.co.uk/News/Columns/Giles_Deacon_new_beach_look_200906167319/|title=Giles Deacon New Beach Look|publisher=Fashion United|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/080910-giles-deacon-launches-menswear.aspx|title=A Giles Kind Of Guy|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|first=Leisa|last=Barnett|date=10 September 2008|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> On 22 March 2010, Deacon and New Look launched his tenth Gold collection.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/7222710/London-Fashion-Week-autumnwinter-2011-designer-preview.html|title=London Fashion Week: autumn/winter 2011 designer preview|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|first=Hilary|last=Alexander|date=15 February 2010|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref> Three years after starting the collaboration with New Look, Deacon said; "My tenth collection focuses on dresses which are easy throw-on pieces with a glamorous edge to ensure that you'll get noticed".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/100309-gold-by-giles-tenth-collection-.aspx|title=Giles' Tenth Look|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|first=Jessica|last=Bumpus|date=9 March 2010|accessdate=11 March 2010}}</ref>

==Recognition==
In 2004, Deacon was named 'Best New Designer' at the [[British Fashion Awards]] and in the following year he was given the Young Designer Award at [[Elle (magazine)|Elle magazine]]'s Style Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fashionunited.co.uk/News/Columns/Giles_Deacon_guest_star_at_Pitti_W_200911107848/|title=Giles Deacon Guest Star At Pitti W|publisher=Fashion United|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="ElleAwards">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3359029/Elle-Style-Awards.html|title=Elle Style Awards|last=Alexander|first=Hilary |date=13 February 2007|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|accessdate=26 March 2010}}</ref> 2006 saw Deacon win the [[British Fashion Council]]'s Fashion Forward Award, as well as being named [[British Fashion Awards|British Fashion Designer of the Year]] at the British Fashion Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishfashioncouncil.com/content.aspx?CategoryID=176|title=Previous Fashion Forward Recipients|work=[[British Fashion Council]]|publisher=[[British Fashion Council]]|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/2006-11/061103-the-2006-winners.aspx|title=The 2006 Winners|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|publisher=[[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]|first=Dolly|last=Jones|date=3 November 2006|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> He was named Best British Designer at the 2007 Elle Style Awards.<ref name="ElleAwards"/> Two years later, Deacon won the French ANDAM Fashion Award's Grand Prix, becoming the second consecutive British designer to win the award following [[Gareth Pugh]]'s win in 2008.<ref name="GilesTelegraph"/> In the same year, he was named [[GQ (magazine)|GQ magazine]]'s Designer of the Year.<ref name="GQ"/>

==Personal Life==
Deacon currently lives in [[Islington]], London.<ref name="GilesSecretLife"/> He has previously dated stylist [[Katie Grand]], who he met at Central St Martins. The couple lived together for a year and a half before splitting amicably.<ref name="GilesKing"/> He has also dated singer [[Beth Orton]] and former model [[Sophie Dahl]].<ref name="EditorsLoveGiles"/><ref name="GilesKing"/> Deacon's hobbies include [[swimming]], [[hiking]] and [[gardening]].<ref name="EditorsLoveGiles"/>

Deacon counts [[Elsa Schiaparelli]], [[Miuccia Prada]], [[Coco Chanel]] and [[Blacks Leisure Group#Millets|Mr J.M. Millet]] among his design inspirations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/fashion/article3369780.ece|title=The Smashing Style Of Giles Deacon|work=[[The Times]]|publisher=[[Times Newspapers Ltd]]|first=Nicola|last=Copping|date=15 February 2008|accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref>

